      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Should You List Your Brisbane Home Vacant, Occupied or Staged in 2026?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The decision shapes your photography, your open homes, your campaign cost and often your final sale price. Here is how the three options actually compare for an inner east Brisbane property in 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Vendors usually arrive at the listing decision with one of three default positions: stay in the property because moving out early feels wasteful, move out and list vacant because the home is empty and the campaign can start immediately, or stage professionally because a neighbour mentioned it adds a hundred thousand to the result. All three positions can be right, and all three can be wrong. The choice depends on the property, the price bracket, the campaign timeline and how honestly you can assess your own household.</p>

      <p>The decision matters because presentation drives the photography, the floorplan reading, and the emotional response in the open home. Each of those inputs feeds the offers you receive. The gap between the best presentation option and the worst, on a comparable Brisbane inner east property, is regularly $40,000 to $120,000 at sale. That is a larger swing than choosing the wrong week to launch, and almost always larger than a 0.5 percent commission negotiation. This article walks through each option in turn and then sets out how to choose.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option one: list the home occupied</h2>
      <p>Listing while you are still living in the property is the most common choice in Brisbane, simply because most sellers cannot or will not move out before settlement. It is logistically simpler, it costs nothing extra beyond your usual living expenses, and it lets you respond to feedback during the campaign without coordinating an empty home from a distance.</p>

      <p>The honest tradeoff is that occupied homes photograph and inspect well only when the household commits to a high presentation standard every day for the duration of the campaign. That is harder than most vendors estimate. Inspection condition means no dishes in the sink, no laundry on the floor, no school bags or work folders on the kitchen bench, no shoes by the door, and beds made every morning before the agent calls to confirm an inspection time. A single relaxed weekend during a six week campaign will produce open home photos and walkthroughs that the agent has to apologise for.</p>

      <p>Occupied campaigns work well for tidy single occupants, couples without young children, and families with older teenagers who genuinely take responsibility for their own spaces. They work less well for families with toddlers, sellers with multiple pets, and households where two adults work from home in different rooms that have become office spaces with cabling, monitors and accumulated paperwork. None of these issues are dealbreakers, but they need a strategy.</p>

      <p>The strategy involves three commitments. First, do a serious declutter and offsite storage exercise before the photographer arrives, removing roughly 30 to 40 percent of personal items, family photographs, fridge magnets, bathroom toiletries and excess furniture. Second, adopt a daily reset routine that takes 15 to 20 minutes each evening and resets each room to presentation condition. Third, vacate the property for every inspection without exception, including weekday mid week inspections, and take pets with you.</p>

      <p>Done well, an occupied home presents warmly and authentically. Buyers see how a family lives in the space, which can be a real advantage in family-oriented suburbs like Camp Hill, Carindale and Coorparoo where the buyer pool is heavily skewed toward young families looking at school catchments. The risk is not that occupied presentation fails. The risk is that it fails inconsistently across the campaign, and buyers form their impression in week two when the household has run out of willpower.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option two: list the home vacant</h2>
      <p>Listing a vacant home appeals because the logistics are simple. You have already moved out, the campaign can start whenever the marketing is ready, inspections can be booked without coordinating with the household, and there is no presentation standard to maintain. The agent gets a key, the photographer gets clean shots, and the open homes run without the family needing to vacate.</p>

      <p>The problem is that vacant homes rarely sell at the top of their price bracket. Empty rooms read as smaller than they actually are because the eye has nothing to scale against. Buyers walk into a 4 by 4 metre bedroom with no bed, no bedside tables and no rug, and they cannot quickly judge whether their own queen bed and wardrobe will fit comfortably. The same room with a styled queen bed, two bedside tables and a styled chair reads as generous because the buyer can mentally place themselves inside it.</p>

      <p>Vacant homes also expose every imperfection. The patch of paint that does not quite match where a picture was rehung, the slight scuff on the timber floor near the kitchen, the small crack in the cornice that nobody noticed when furniture stood beneath it, the carpet impression where a sofa used to live. Without anything else in the room to look at, the buyer fixates on the flaw. Photography becomes harder because there is no warmth in the frame, just walls and floors, which produces listing images that the major portals struggle to make compelling.</p>

      <p>The strongest result a vacant property tends to produce in Brisbane's inner east is mid range for its comparable band. A four bedroom Queenslander in Morningside that should comp at $1.65 million furnished tends to sell at $1.55 to $1.6 million empty, unless something else in the campaign produces unusual buyer competition. That gap is consistent enough across inner east sales that it is the strongest argument for adding even a partial stage to a vacant property.</p>

      <p>If listing vacant is unavoidable because of a relocation, an estate timing constraint, or a property that has been empty for months, the right move is partial staging of the rooms that drive buyer decisions. Stage the living room, the principal bedroom and the outdoor entertaining area at minimum. Add virtual staging to the secondary bedroom photos on the portals. The combined cost is usually $2,500 to $4,500, and it closes most of the gap to a fully presented home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option three: list the home professionally staged</h2>
      <p>Professional staging means a stylist removes some or all of your existing furniture, brings in their own pieces selected for the property and the target buyer, and leaves the home set for inspection from photography day through to contract signing. The home you live in becomes a styled showroom for four to eight weeks.</p>

      <p>The cost in Brisbane in 2026 sits in a predictable range. Full property staging on an average inner east home over a six week hire runs $3,500 to $9,000, depending on the size of the property and the level of finish the stylist is sourcing. Premium full stages on larger homes in Bulimba, Hawthorne and Norman Park can reach $12,000 to $18,000 over an extended eight week hire. Hero room only stages, covering the living room and principal bedroom while the rest of the home stays in its existing state, sit around $1,500 to $2,500. Partial staging of empty rooms in an otherwise furnished home runs $1,800 to $3,500.</p>

      <p>The case for staging is straightforward arithmetic on most homes priced above $1 million. A 1 percent uplift on a $1.2 million sale price is $12,000. A 2 percent uplift is $24,000. Even modest staging that produces a 1.5 percent uplift more than covers its cost, and the inner east data on comparable sales consistently supports a 2 to 4 percent uplift on properly staged homes relative to identical homes presented poorly. The cost is also a fully deductible selling expense for tax purposes when calculating the cost base of an investment property sale.</p>

      <p>Staging works best when it is matched to the property type and the buyer profile. A modern townhouse in West End targeting professional couples and downsizers should be staged in a clean contemporary palette with high quality lighting and minimal clutter. A renovated Queenslander in Camp Hill targeting young families should be staged warmly with reading nooks, well chosen artwork and a sense that the home is loved. A federation cottage in Norman Park targeting first home buyers should be staged simply, showing the bones of the home rather than overwhelming it. The wrong style on the right property, or vice versa, wastes the spend.</p>

      <p>The case against staging is that you lose use of the home during the campaign. You either move out for six weeks, which adds short term accommodation costs, or you live around the stylist's furniture with strict instructions not to use the styled rooms. For families this is rarely workable. The more common pattern in Brisbane is for the seller to move out the week of photography, stay in short term accommodation or with family for four to six weeks until contracts are exchanged, and return only briefly for inspections and settlement preparation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which option suits which property</h2>
      <p>The decision rarely sits on a single factor, but a few patterns hold across the inner east. Owner occupier homes priced above $1.2 million almost always justify professional staging, full or partial, because the buyer pool is making an emotional decision at a price point where 2 percent is real money. Family homes in the $900,000 to $1.2 million range can go either way, with occupied presentation working well if the household genuinely holds the standard, or partial hero room staging closing the gap if the household cannot.</p>

      <p>Vacant listings should be the last choice in nearly every case. If the home is already empty and a full stage is not feasible, partial staging plus virtual photography is almost always the right add on. Investment properties being sold at the end of a tenancy sit in their own category: a brief lease break, a deep clean, partial staging of two key rooms, and an aggressive four week campaign tends to outperform a hurried sale with the property left exactly as the tenant lived in it.</p>

      <p>The exception that proves the rule is small apartments and units priced below $700,000. The cost of full staging eats into the result too aggressively at that price point, and the buyer pool is more practical, valuing the layout and the bones of the property over the styling. A clean, decluttered, occupied apartment with good professional photography and a small spend on a few staged accent pieces consistently outperforms a fully staged apartment at this price range, because the marginal uplift no longer justifies the marginal cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The hybrid approach most sellers actually take</h2>
      <p>The cleanest version of this decision often turns out to be a hybrid. You stay in the property for the campaign, but you commit to a serious pre photography declutter that removes 30 to 40 percent of your furniture and personal items into offsite storage for six weeks. You add hero room staging in the living room and primary bedroom, using the stylist's furniture and accessories to lift those two rooms to the level of a full stage. You hold the daily presentation standard with a 20 minute evening routine and vacate every inspection.</p>

      <p>The total cost of this approach is typically $1,800 to $3,200 for the hero room hire plus $400 to $600 for offsite storage for six weeks. It captures most of the uplift of a full stage without the cost or the disruption of vacating the property. For Brisbane sellers in the $900,000 to $1.5 million bracket, this is the option that produces the best risk adjusted outcome on most campaigns.</p>

      <p>The hybrid also gives you a fallback. If feedback in the first two weeks of the campaign suggests the property is presenting strongly and offers are coming in well, you continue as planned. If feedback suggests buyers are struggling to see the scale of the secondary bedrooms or the home is reading as cluttered despite your declutter, you can add a second stage on the weaker rooms in week three and reset the campaign with refreshed marketing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to decide</h2>
      <p>Walk through four questions before you commit. First, what is the realistic price band for the property, and does a 2 percent uplift cover the cost of full staging with margin to spare? If yes, staging is usually the right call. Second, can your household honestly hold a presentation standard every day for six weeks across every room of the home? If no, occupied is the wrong default and you need either a hybrid or a full stage. Third, is the home currently vacant, and if so, are you genuinely unable to add partial staging? If you are able, add it. Fourth, what is the buyer pool likely to be, and what style of presentation do they respond to in your suburb and price bracket?</p>

      <p>For most inner east Brisbane sellers in 2026, the answer lands on either professional staging or the hybrid approach. Pure occupied campaigns are workable but underperform unless the household is unusually disciplined. Pure vacant campaigns are the lowest yield option and should be avoided unless there is no alternative. The right answer for your specific property depends on the price bracket, the buyer profile and your honest assessment of how the home will look on a Tuesday afternoon in week three of the campaign. An experienced local agent should walk through the options with you before listing day, not after.</p>

